**📘 MODULE 4: The this Keyword — Complete Deep Dive**

**🧠 4.1 — What is this?**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    THE `this` KEYWORD                        │
│                                                              │
│  `this` is a special keyword in JavaScript that refers to    │
│  the OBJECT that is currently executing the function.        │
│                                                              │
│  KEY PRINCIPLE:                                              │
│  `this` is NOT determined by where a function is written.    │
│  `this` is determined by HOW the function is CALLED.         │
│                                                              │
│  (Exception: Arrow functions — they use lexical `this`)      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**🧠 4.2 — The 5 Rules of this Binding**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              5 RULES OF `this` (Priority Order)              │
│                                                              │
│  Rule 1: DEFAULT Binding        → Global object / undefined  │
│  Rule 2: IMPLICIT Binding       → Object before the dot     │
│  Rule 3: EXPLICIT Binding       → call, apply, bind         │
│  Rule 4: NEW Binding            → Newly created object      │
│  Rule 5: ARROW Function         → Lexical this (parent)     │
│                                                              │
│  Priority: new > explicit > implicit > default               │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**Rule 1: Default Binding**

```
function showThis() {
    console.log(this);
}

showThis();
text
In Browser (non-strict mode):
  Output: Window object

In Browser (strict mode):
  "use strict";
  Output: undefined

In Node.js:
  Output: global object (or undefined in strict mode)
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  DEFAULT BINDING RULE                                        │
│                                                              │
│  When a function is called WITHOUT any object reference:     │
│                                                              │
│  Non-strict mode → this = global object (window in browser)  │
│  Strict mode     → this = undefined                          │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
More Default Binding Examples:
var name = "Global Rahul";

function greet() {
    console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
}

greet();  // "Hello, Global Rahul" (non-strict mode)
          // this = window, window.name = "Global Rahul"
"use strict";

function test() {
    console.log(this);
}

test();  // undefined

function test2() {
    console.log(this.name);  // TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined
}

test2();
```

**Rule 2: Implicit Binding**

```
var person = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    }
};

person.greet();  // "Hello, Rahul"

┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  IMPLICIT BINDING RULE                                       │
│                                                              │
│  When a function is called as a METHOD of an object:         │
│  this = the object LEFT of the dot (.)                       │
│                                                              │
│  person.greet()  →  this = person                            │
│  obj.method()    →  this = obj                               │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Nested Object — Only Immediate Parent Matters:

var company = {
    name: "TechCorp",
    department: {
        name: "Engineering",
        getTeam: function() {
            console.log(this.name);
        }
    }
};

company.department.getTeam();  // "Engineering" (NOT "TechCorp")

Why? this = the object IMMEDIATELY before the dot.
company.department.getTeam() → this = company.department

🔥 Implicit Binding LOSS (Common Bug):

var person = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    }
};

var greetFn = person.greet;  // Extracting the function
greetFn();  // "Hello, undefined" (or "Hello, " in browser)

┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  IMPLICIT BINDING LOSS                                       │
│                                                              │
│  When you extract a method from an object and call it        │
│  without the object reference, implicit binding is LOST.     │
│                                                              │
│  var fn = obj.method;                                        │
│  fn();  // this = global (not obj!)                          │
│                                                              │
│  This is one of the MOST COMMON bugs in JavaScript.          │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Implicit Binding Loss with Callbacks:

var person = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    }
};

setTimeout(person.greet, 1000);  // "Hello, undefined"

// setTimeout receives the function reference, not the object
// It calls the function without any object context
// So default binding applies: this = window (or undefined in strict)
```

**Rule 3: Explicit Binding (call, apply, bind)**

**call() — Call with arguments listed individually**

```
function greet(greeting, punctuation) {
    console.log(greeting + ", " + this.name + punctuation);
}

var person = { name: "Rahul" };

greet.call(person, "Hello", "!");
// Output: "Hello, Rahul!"
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  call() SYNTAX                                               │
│                                                              │
│  function.call(thisArg, arg1, arg2, ...)                     │
│                                                              │
│  - First argument becomes `this`                             │
│  - Remaining arguments passed individually                   │
│  - Function is IMMEDIATELY invoked                           │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
apply() — Call with arguments as array
JavaScript
function greet(greeting, punctuation) {
    console.log(greeting + ", " + this.name + punctuation);
}

var person = { name: "Priya" };

greet.apply(person, ["Namaste", "!"]);
// Output: "Namaste, Priya!"
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  apply() SYNTAX                                              │
│                                                              │
│  function.apply(thisArg, [arg1, arg2, ...])                  │
│                                                              │
│  - First argument becomes `this`                             │
│  - Second argument is an ARRAY of arguments                  │
│  - Function is IMMEDIATELY invoked                           │
│                                                              │
│  MEMORY AID:                                                 │
│  call → C = Comma separated arguments                        │
│  apply → A = Array of arguments                              │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**bind() — Returns a new function with fixed this**

```
function greet() {
    console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
}

var person = { name: "Rahul" };

var boundGreet = greet.bind(person);

boundGreet();  // "Hello, Rahul"
boundGreet();  // "Hello, Rahul"  (always bound to person)

┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  bind() SYNTAX                                               │
│                                                              │
│  var newFn = function.bind(thisArg, arg1, arg2, ...)         │
│                                                              │
│  - Returns a NEW function (does NOT invoke immediately)      │
│  - The returned function has `this` permanently set          │
│  - Can also pre-fill arguments (partial application)         │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Practical bind Example:

var person = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    }
};

// Fix the implicit binding loss:
setTimeout(person.greet.bind(person), 1000);
// Output after 1 second: "Hello, Rahul" ✅
Partial Application with bind:

function multiply(a, b) {
    return a * b;
}

var double = multiply.bind(null, 2);  // a is fixed as 2
var triple = multiply.bind(null, 3);  // a is fixed as 3

console.log(double(5));   // 10
console.log(double(10));  // 20
console.log(triple(5));   // 15

bind Polyfill (Interview Favorite):

Function.prototype.myBind = function(context) {
    if (typeof this !== "function") {
        throw new Error("Not a function");
    }

    var fn = this;
    var outerArgs = Array.prototype.slice.call(arguments, 1);

    return function() {
        var innerArgs = Array.prototype.slice.call(arguments);
        return fn.apply(context, outerArgs.concat(innerArgs));
    };
};

// Test:
function greet(greeting, punctuation) {
    console.log(greeting + ", " + this.name + punctuation);
}

var person = { name: "Rahul" };
var bound = greet.myBind(person, "Hello");
bound("!");  // "Hello, Rahul!"

┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  BIND POLYFILL BREAKDOWN                                     │
│                                                              │
│  1. Capture the original function (this)                     │
│  2. Capture pre-filled arguments (outerArgs)                 │
│  3. Return a new function that:                              │
│     a. Captures any new arguments (innerArgs)                │
│     b. Calls original function with apply()                  │
│     c. Passes the fixed context                              │
│     d. Merges outer + inner arguments                        │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Rule 4:** new **Binding**

```
function Person(name, age) {
    // this = {} (new empty object created automatically)
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
    // return this (happens automatically)
}

var p1 = new Person("Rahul", 25);
console.log(p1.name);  // "Rahul"
console.log(p1.age);   // 25
console.log(p1);       // Person { name: "Rahul", age: 25 }
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  WHAT `new` DOES (4 Steps)                                   │
│                                                              │
│  Step 1: Creates a new empty object {}                       │
│  Step 2: Sets the prototype of this object                   │
│  Step 3: Binds `this` to the new object                      │
│  Step 4: Returns the object (unless function returns         │
│          another object explicitly)                           │
│                                                              │
│  function Person(name) {                                     │
│      // this = {}              ← Step 1 & 3                  │
│      this.name = name;         ← Adding properties           │
│      // return this            ← Step 4 (implicit)           │
│  }                                                           │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
new overrides explicit binding:
JavaScript
function Foo(name) {
    this.name = name;
}

var obj = { name: "existing" };

var boundFoo = Foo.bind(obj);
var instance = new boundFoo("New Name");

console.log(instance.name);  // "New Name" (new binding wins!)
console.log(obj.name);       // "existing" (unchanged)
```

**Rule 5: Arrow Functions (this is Lexical)**

```
var person = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greet: function() {
        var inner = () => {
            console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
        };
        inner();
    }
};

person.greet();  // "Hello, Rahul"
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ARROW FUNCTION `this` RULE                                  │
│                                                              │
│  Arrow functions DO NOT have their own `this`.               │
│  They INHERIT `this` from the enclosing lexical scope.       │
│                                                              │
│  In the example above:                                       │
│  - greet() is called with person (implicit binding)          │
│  - this = person inside greet()                              │
│  - Arrow function inner() inherits this = person             │
│  - So this.name = "Rahul"                                    │
│                                                              │
│  Arrow functions CANNOT be changed with call/apply/bind.     │
│  Arrow functions CANNOT be used as constructors.             │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Arrow Function vs Regular Function Comparison:
JavaScript
var person = {
    name: "Rahul",

    // Regular function — this = person (implicit binding)
    regularGreet: function() {
        console.log("Regular: " + this.name);
    },

    // Arrow function — this = global (lexical, from where object is defined)
    arrowGreet: () => {
        console.log("Arrow: " + this.name);
    }
};

person.regularGreet();  // "Regular: Rahul" ✅
person.arrowGreet();    // "Arrow: undefined" ❌
text
Why does arrowGreet fail?

The arrow function is defined inside the person object literal.
The enclosing scope of the object literal is GLOBAL scope.
So arrow function's `this` = global object (window).
window.name is undefined (or empty string).

LESSON: Never use arrow functions as object methods!
Arrow Function in Event Handlers:
JavaScript
// ❌ BAD — Arrow function loses element context
document.getElementById("btn").addEventListener("click", () => {
    console.log(this);  // Window object, NOT the button!
});

// ✅ GOOD — Regular function gets element as this
document.getElementById("btn").addEventListener("click", function() {
    console.log(this);  // The button element
});
Arrow Function in setTimeout (Useful Pattern):
JavaScript
var person = {
    name: "Rahul",
    greetLater: function() {
        // ❌ Regular function — this is lost in setTimeout
        setTimeout(function() {
            console.log("Regular: " + this.name);  // undefined
        }, 1000);

        // ✅ Arrow function — inherits this from greetLater
        setTimeout(() => {
            console.log("Arrow: " + this.name);  // "Rahul"
        }, 1000);
    }
};

person.greetLater();
text
Output after 1 second:
Regular: undefined
Arrow: Rahul

**🔥 this in Classes:**

class User {
    constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    greet() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    }

    greetLater() {
        setTimeout(() => {
            console.log("Later: " + this.name);  // Arrow inherits class this
        }, 1000);
    }
}

var user = new User("Rahul");
user.greet();       // "Hello, Rahul"
user.greetLater();  // After 1s: "Later: Rahul"

// But watch out for binding loss:
var fn = user.greet;
fn();  // "Hello, undefined" — binding lost!

// Fix:
var boundFn = user.greet.bind(user);
boundFn();  // "Hello, Rahul"

```

