**🌍 Real-World Scenario: this Bug in React Class Component**

```
// ❌ BUG in React class component
class Button extends React.Component {
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = { count: 0 };
    }

    handleClick() {
        // BUG: this is undefined here because of binding loss!
        this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 });
    }

    render() {
        return <button onClick={this.handleClick}>Click</button>;
        // this.handleClick is extracted as a reference
        // When called by React, implicit binding is LOST
    }
}

// ✅ FIX 1: Bind in constructor
constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.handleClick = this.handleClick.bind(this);
}

// ✅ FIX 2: Arrow function in class
handleClick = () => {
    this.setState({ count: this.state.count + 1 });
};

// ✅ FIX 3: Arrow function in render
render() {
    return <button onClick={() => this.handleClick()}>Click</button>;
}

```

# **📘 MODULE 5: Prototypes & Inheritance — Complete Deep Dive**

## **🧠 5.1 — What is a Prototype?**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     PROTOTYPES                               │
│                                                              │
│  Every object in JavaScript has a hidden internal property   │
│  called [[Prototype]] (accessible via __proto__).            │
│                                                              │
│  This prototype is ANOTHER OBJECT from which the current     │
│  object can inherit properties and methods.                  │
│                                                              │
│  When you access a property on an object:                    │
│  1. JS looks on the object itself                            │
│  2. If not found, looks on its prototype                     │
│  3. If not found, looks on prototype's prototype             │
│  4. Continues until null (end of chain)                      │
│                                                              │
│  This is called the PROTOTYPE CHAIN.                         │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Basic Prototype Example:
JavaScript
var person = {
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    }
};

var rahul = {
    name: "Rahul"
};

// Set person as the prototype of rahul
rahul.__proto__ = person;

rahul.greet();  // "Hello, Rahul"
text
How it works:

rahul.greet()
  → JS looks for greet on rahul → Not found
  → JS looks on rahul.__proto__ (which is person) → Found!
  → Calls person.greet() with this = rahul
  → "Hello, Rahul"
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  PROTOTYPE CHAIN VISUAL                                      │
│                                                              │
│  rahul { name: "Rahul" }                                     │
│    │                                                         │
│    │ __proto__                                               │
│    ▼                                                         │
│  person { greet: function() {...} }                          │
│    │                                                         │
│    │ __proto__                                               │
│    ▼                                                         │
│  Object.prototype { toString, hasOwnProperty, ... }          │
│    │                                                         │
│    │ __proto__                                               │
│    ▼                                                         │
│  null (END of chain)                                         │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**🧠 5.2 — __proto__ vs prototype**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  __proto__ vs prototype — THE MOST CONFUSING TOPIC           │
│                                                              │
│  __proto__:                                                  │
│  - EXISTS on every object                                    │
│  - Points to the object's prototype (parent)                 │
│  - Used for LOOKUP (reading inheritance chain)               │
│                                                              │
│  prototype:                                                  │
│  - EXISTS only on FUNCTIONS                                  │
│  - Is an object that will become the __proto__ of            │
│    instances created with `new`                              │
│  - Used for SETTING UP inheritance                           │
│                                                              │
│  EXAMPLE:                                                    │
│  function Person(name) { this.name = name; }                 │
│  var p = new Person("Rahul");                                │
│                                                              │
│  p.__proto__ === Person.prototype  // true                   │
│  Person.prototype is the TEMPLATE                            │
│  p.__proto__ is the LINK to that template                    │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**Visual:**

```
function Animal(name) {
    this.name = name;
}

Animal.prototype.speak = function() {
    console.log(this.name + " makes a sound");
};

var dog = new Animal("Dog");
var cat = new Animal("Cat");

dog.speak();  // "Dog makes a sound"
cat.speak();  // "Cat makes a sound"
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                              │
│  Animal (function)                                           │
│  ├── prototype ──▶ { speak: function() {...} }               │
│                         ▲           ▲                        │
│                         │           │                        │
│  dog ──▶ __proto__ ─────┘           │                        │
│  { name: "Dog" }                    │                        │
│                                     │                        │
│  cat ──▶ __proto__ ─────────────────┘                        │
│  { name: "Cat" }                                             │
│                                                              │
│  BOTH dog and cat SHARE the same speak method!               │
│  Memory efficient — method exists only once.                 │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**🧠 5.3 — Constructor Functions**

```
function Person(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
}

Person.prototype.greet = function() {
    console.log("Hi, I'm " + this.name + ", age " + this.age);
};

Person.prototype.isAdult = function() {
    return this.age >= 18;
};

var p1 = new Person("Rahul", 25);
var p2 = new Person("Priya", 16);

p1.greet();              // "Hi, I'm Rahul, age 25"
p2.greet();              // "Hi, I'm Priya, age 16"
console.log(p1.isAdult());  // true
console.log(p2.isAdult());  // false

// Verification:
console.log(p1.__proto__ === Person.prototype);  // true
console.log(p2.__proto__ === Person.prototype);  // true
console.log(p1.greet === p2.greet);              // true (same function!)
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  WHY PUT METHODS ON prototype?                               │
│                                                              │
│  If greet was inside the constructor:                        │
│  function Person(name) {                                     │
│      this.name = name;                                       │
│      this.greet = function() { ... };  // NEW copy each time │
│  }                                                           │
│                                                              │
│  Each instance gets its OWN copy of greet → wastes memory    │
│                                                              │
│  If greet is on prototype:                                   │
│  Person.prototype.greet = function() { ... };                │
│                                                              │
│  All instances SHARE one copy of greet → memory efficient    │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**🧠 5.4 — Object.create()**

```
var personProto = {
    greet: function() {
        console.log("Hello, " + this.name);
    },
    isAdult: function() {
        return this.age >= 18;
    }
};

var rahul = Object.create(personProto);
rahul.name = "Rahul";
rahul.age = 25;

rahul.greet();             // "Hello, Rahul"
console.log(rahul.isAdult());  // true

console.log(rahul.__proto__ === personProto);  // true
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Object.create(proto)                                        │
│                                                              │
│  Creates a new empty object with __proto__ set to proto.     │
│                                                              │
│  This is the CLEANEST way to set up inheritance.             │
│  No constructor function needed.                             │
│                                                              │
│  Object.create(null) creates an object with NO prototype     │
│  (no toString, no hasOwnProperty — truly empty)              │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**🧠 5.5 — Prototypal Inheritance (Creating Subclasses)**

```
function Animal(name) {
    this.name = name;
}

Animal.prototype.speak = function() {
    console.log(this.name + " makes a sound");
};

function Dog(name, breed) {
    Animal.call(this, name);  // Call parent constructor
    this.breed = breed;
}

// Set up inheritance chain
Dog.prototype = Object.create(Animal.prototype);
Dog.prototype.constructor = Dog;  // Fix constructor reference

// Add Dog-specific method
Dog.prototype.bark = function() {
    console.log(this.name + " barks: Woof!");
};

// Override parent method
Dog.prototype.speak = function() {
    console.log(this.name + " barks loudly!");
};

var dog = new Dog("Rex", "German Shepherd");

dog.bark();   // "Rex barks: Woof!"
dog.speak();  // "Rex barks loudly!" (overridden)
console.log(dog.name);   // "Rex"
console.log(dog.breed);  // "German Shepherd"
console.log(dog instanceof Dog);     // true
console.log(dog instanceof Animal);  // true
text
PROTOTYPE CHAIN:

dog { name: "Rex", breed: "German Shepherd" }
  │
  │ __proto__
  ▼
Dog.prototype { bark: fn, speak: fn (overridden), constructor: Dog }
  │
  │ __proto__
  ▼
Animal.prototype { speak: fn (original), constructor: Animal }
  │
  │ __proto__
  ▼
Object.prototype { toString, hasOwnProperty, ... }
  │
  │ __proto__
  ▼
null
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  PROTOTYPAL INHERITANCE STEPS                                │
│                                                              │
│  1. Call parent constructor: Parent.call(this, args)         │
│  2. Set prototype chain: Child.prototype = Object.create(    │
│     Parent.prototype)                                        │
│  3. Fix constructor: Child.prototype.constructor = Child     │
│  4. Add child methods to Child.prototype                     │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**🧠 5.6 — ES6 Class Syntax (Syntactic Sugar over Prototypes)**

```
class Animal {
    constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    speak() {
        console.log(this.name + " makes a sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    constructor(name, breed) {
        super(name);  // Calls Animal's constructor
        this.breed = breed;
    }

    bark() {
        console.log(this.name + " barks: Woof!");
    }

    speak() {  // Override parent method
        super.speak();  // Call parent's speak
        console.log(this.name + " barks specifically!");
    }
}

var dog = new Dog("Rex", "Lab");
dog.speak();
// "Rex makes a sound"
// "Rex barks specifically!"
dog.bark();  // "Rex barks: Woof!"
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ES6 CLASSES ARE SYNTACTIC SUGAR                             │
│                                                              │
│  Under the hood, it's still prototypal inheritance!          │
│                                                              │
│  class Animal { ... }                                        │
│  is equivalent to:                                           │
│  function Animal() { ... }                                   │
│  Animal.function Person(name) {
    this.name = name;
}

Person.prototype.species = "Human";

var p = new Person("Rahul");

console.log(p.hasOwnProperty("name"));     // true (own property)
console.log(p.hasOwnProperty("species"));  // false (inherited)

console.log("name" in p);      // true (found on object)
console.log("species" in p);   // true (found on prototype chain)
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  hasOwnProperty → Only checks the object ITSELF              │
│  in operator    → Checks object AND its prototype chain      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
.speak = function() { ... }                 │
│                                                              │
│  class Dog extends Animal { ... }                            │
│  is equivalent to:                                           │
│  function Dog() { Animal.call(this, ...); ... }              │
│  Dog.prototype = Object.create(Animal.prototype);            │
│                                                              │
│  Proof:                                                      │
│  typeof Animal === "function"  // true!                      │
│  Dog.prototype.__proto__ === Animal.prototype  // true!      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**🧠 5.7 — hasOwnProperty vs in Operator**

```
function Person(name) {
    this.name = name;
}

Person.prototype.species = "Human";

var p = new Person("Rahul");

console.log(p.hasOwnProperty("name"));     // true (own property)
console.log(p.hasOwnProperty("species"));  // false (inherited)

console.log("name" in p);      // true (found on object)
console.log("species" in p);   // true (found on prototype chain)
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  hasOwnProperty → Only checks the object ITSELF              │
│  in operator    → Checks object AND its prototype chain      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

```
🧠 5.8 — Prototype Pollution (Security Issue)
JavaScript
// ❌ DANGER: Prototype Pollution Attack
var malicious = JSON.parse('{"__proto__": {"isAdmin": true}}');

// If a library does:
// Object.assign(target, malicious)
// or deep merge without sanitization

var user = {};
console.log(user.isAdmin);  // Could be true if prototype was polluted!
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  PROTOTYPE POLLUTION PREVENTION                              │
│                                                              │
│  1. Use Object.create(null) for dictionaries                 │
│  2. Validate keys — reject __proto__, constructor, prototype │
│  3. Use Map instead of plain objects for user input           │
│  4. Freeze prototypes: Object.freeze(Object.prototype)       │
│  5. Use libraries that sanitize deep merges                  │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

## **📝 MODULE 5 — Practice Questions**

### **🟢 Easy**

Q1: What is the output?

```
