# **📘 MODULE 6: Event Loop — Complete Deep Dive**

---

## **🧠 6.1 — JavaScript is Single-Threaded**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  JAVASCRIPT'S CORE NATURE                                    │
│                                                              │
│  JavaScript is SINGLE-THREADED.                              │
│  It has ONE call stack.                                      │
│  It can execute ONE thing at a time.                         │
│                                                              │
│  But web applications need:                                  │
│  - API calls (network requests)                              │
│  - Timers (setTimeout, setInterval)                          │
│  - User events (clicks, scrolls)                             │
│  - File operations                                           │
│                                                              │
│  How does JS handle async operations?                        │
│  Answer: The EVENT LOOP + Web APIs + Task Queues             │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

```

**🧠 6.2 — The Complete Runtime Architecture**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    JAVASCRIPT RUNTIME ENVIRONMENT                    │
│                                                                      │
│  ┌──────────────────────┐      ┌────────────────────────────┐        │
│  │     CALL STACK        │      │        WEB APIs            │        │
│  │                      │      │   (Browser provides)       │        │
│  │  ┌────────────────┐  │      │                            │        │
│  │  │   function C    │  │      │  • setTimeout/setInterval  │        │
│  │  ├────────────────┤  │      │  • fetch / XMLHttpRequest  │        │
│  │  │   function B    │  │      │  • DOM Events (click, etc) │        │
│  │  ├────────────────┤  │      │  • Geolocation API         │        │
│  │  │   function A    │  │      │  • Console                 │        │
│  │  ├────────────────┤  │      │  • Local Storage           │        │
│  │  │ Global Context  │  │      │                            │        │
│  │  └────────────────┘  │      └──────────┬─────────────────┘        │
│  └──────────────────────┘                 │                          │
│                                           │ When async operation     │
│                                           │ completes, callback      │
│                                           │ goes to queue            │
│                                           ▼                          │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐     │
│  │                    TASK QUEUES                               │     │
│  │                                                              │     │
│  │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐      │     │
│  │  │  MICROTASK QUEUE (Higher Priority)                 │      │     │
│  │  │  • Promise callbacks (.then, .catch, .finally)     │      │     │
│  │  │  • queueMicrotask()                                │      │     │
│  │  │  • MutationObserver                                │      │     │
│  │  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘      │     │
│  │                                                              │     │
│  │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐      │     │
│  │  │  MACROTASK QUEUE (Lower Priority)                  │      │     │
│  │  │  • setTimeout / setInterval callbacks              │      │     │
│  │  │  • DOM event callbacks                             │      │     │
│  │  │  • I/O operations                                  │      │     │
│  │  │  • setImmediate (Node.js)                          │      │     │
│  │  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘      │     │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘     │
│                                                                      │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │                    EVENT LOOP                                 │    │
│  │                                                              │    │
│  │  Continuously checks:                                        │    │
│  │  1. Is call stack empty?                                     │    │
│  │     └── NO → Wait                                            │    │
│  │     └── YES ↓                                                │    │
│  │  2. Are there microtasks?                                    │    │
│  │     └── YES → Execute ALL microtasks first                   │    │
│  │     └── NO ↓                                                 │    │
│  │  3. Are there macrotasks?                                    │    │
│  │     └── YES → Execute ONE macrotask                          │    │
│  │     └── Then go back to step 1                               │    │
│  └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## **🧠 6.3 — Step-by-Step Event Loop Execution**

### **Example 1: Basic setTimeout**

```
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(function() {
    console.log("Timer");
}, 0);

console.log("End");
Step-by-step trace:
text
Step 1: console.log("Start") → Push to call stack → Execute → Print "Start" → Pop

Step 2: setTimeout(fn, 0) → Push to call stack → Registers callback with Web API
        → setTimeout pops off call stack
        → Web API starts 0ms timer
        → Timer completes immediately → callback moves to MACROTASK queue

Step 3: console.log("End") → Push to call stack → Execute → Print "End" → Pop

Step 4: Call stack is NOW EMPTY
        → Event loop checks: Any microtasks? NO
        → Event loop checks: Any macrotasks? YES
        → Move callback to call stack → Execute → Print "Timer" → Pop

Output:
Start
End
Timer
text
WHY "Timer" comes last even with 0ms delay?

setTimeout(fn, 0) does NOT mean "execute immediately".
It means "execute as soon as possible AFTER the call stack is empty".
The current synchronous code ALWAYS finishes first.

Example 2: Promises vs setTimeout
JavaScript
