🧠 7.2 — What is a Promise?
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    PROMISE DEFINITION                         │
│                                                              │
│  A Promise is an OBJECT representing the eventual            │
│  completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation.        │
│                                                              │
│  Think of it as a placeholder for a FUTURE value.            │
│                                                              │
│  Real-life analogy:                                          │
│  You order food at a restaurant.                             │
│  The waiter gives you a TOKEN (promise).                     │
│  The token is initially PENDING.                             │
│  Later it either:                                            │
│    - FULFILLED: You get your food                            │
│    - REJECTED: Kitchen ran out of ingredients                │
│                                                              │
│  3 STATES:                                                   │
│  ┌──────────┐    ┌──────────────┐                            │
│  │ PENDING  │───▶│  FULFILLED   │  (resolved with a value)   │
│  │          │    └──────────────┘                            │
│  │          │    ┌──────────────┐                            │
│  │          │───▶│  REJECTED    │  (rejected with a reason)  │
│  └──────────┘    └──────────────┘                            │
│                                                              │
│  Once settled (fulfilled/rejected), state CANNOT change.     │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Creating a Promise:
JavaScript
var promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
    // Async operation
    var success = true;

    if (success) {
        resolve("Data fetched successfully!");  // Fulfill
    } else {
        reject("Something went wrong!");        // Reject
    }
});

// Consuming the promise:
promise
    .then(function(value) {
        console.log("Success:", value);
    })
    .catch(function(error) {
        console.log("Error:", error);
    });
text
Output: Success: Data fetched successfully!

