🧠 7.6 — Async/Await (Syntactic Sugar over Promises)
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  ASYNC/AWAIT                                                 │
│                                                              │
│  async function → Always returns a Promise                   │
│  await          → Pauses execution until Promise resolves    │
│                                                              │
│  Makes async code LOOK and BEHAVE like synchronous code.     │
│  Under the hood, it's still Promises and microtasks.         │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Basic Async/Await:
JavaScript
function delay(ms) {
    return new Promise(function(resolve) {
        setTimeout(resolve, ms);
    });
}

async function greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
    await delay(2000);
    console.log("World");  // Prints after 2 seconds
}

greet();
console.log("This runs immediately!");
text
Output:
Hello
This runs immediately!
World (after 2 seconds)
Promise Chain vs Async/Await:
JavaScript
// ✅ Promise chain version:
function getUser() {
    return fetchUser()
        .then(function(user) {
            return fetchOrders(user.id);
        })
        .then(function(orders) {
            return fetchDetails(orders[0].id);
        })
        .then(function(details) {
            console.log(details);
        })
        .catch(function(err) {
            console.error(err);
        });
}

// ✅ Async/Await version (same logic, cleaner):
async function getUser() {
    try {
        var user = await fetchUser();
        var orders = await fetchOrders(user.id);
        var details = await fetchDetails(orders[0].id);
        console.log(details);
    } catch (err) {
        console.error(err);
    }
}

Error Handling with Async/Await:
JavaScript
async function riskyOperation() {
    try {
        var response = await fetch("/api/data");

        if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error("HTTP Error: " + response.status);
        }

        var data = await response.json();
        console.log("Data:", data);
        return data;

    } catch (error) {
        console.error("Failed:", error.message);
        throw error;  // Re-throw if caller needs to know

    } finally {
        console.log("Operation complete");  // Always runs
    }
}

Parallel Execution with Async/Await:
JavaScript
// ❌ SEQUENTIAL — Slow (6 seconds total)
async function sequential() {
    var a = await delay2sec();  // Wait 2 seconds
    var b = await delay2sec();  // Wait 2 more seconds
    var c = await delay2sec();  // Wait 2 more seconds
    return a + b + c;
}

// ✅ PARALLEL — Fast (2 seconds total)
async function parallel() {
    var [a, b, c] = await Promise.all([
        delay2sec(),
        delay2sec(),
        delay2sec()
    ]);
    return a + b + c;
}
text
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  COMMON MISTAKE                                              │
│                                                              │
│  Using await in a loop makes things SEQUENTIAL:              │
│                                                              │
│  ❌ for (var url of urls) {                                  │
│       var data = await fetch(url);  // One at a time!        │
│     }                                                        │
│                                                              │
│  ✅ var promises = urls.map(url => fetch(url));              │
│     var results = await Promise.all(promises);  // Parallel! │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

