║              INTERFACE VS TYPE ALIAS                          ║
╠═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣
║                                                               ║
║  USE INTERFACE WHEN:                                          ║
║  • Defining object shapes (especially for public APIs)        ║
║  • You need declaration merging                               ║
║  • Defining class contracts                                   ║
║  • You want extends/implements                                ║
║                                                               ║
║  USE TYPE ALIAS WHEN:                                         ║
║  • Creating union types                                       ║
║  • Creating intersection types                                ║
║  • Working with tuples                                        ║
║  • Creating mapped types                                      ║
║  • Creating conditional types                                 ║
║  • Aliasing primitives or function types                      ║
║                                                               ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
*/

// Interface - Can be merged
interface User {
